ard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bippinfv>bippinfv</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elf-hugger</span><br>  Posts: 942<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/10/02 2:02:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3258.topic&index=21>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Introduction to Roleplaying</span><hr size=1> Cop out! There's no uniform way to &quot;pantomime&quot; that expression. If you want to pantomime it, just do so. E.g.:<br>
<br>
/em presents a pack of bandages in one hand, and a few food rations in the other.<br>
<br>
In my view, emotes are actions, pure and simple, while /say or /g are talking. <br>
Sometimes I see emotes used to &quot;qualify&quot; speech, such as:<br>
/em whispers &quot;do you want to go somewhere more private?&quot;<br>
<br>
It can also be done in say, by using some marker for the emoted part:<br>
/say *whispers* Do you want to go somewhere less crowded?<br>
<br>
It is up to others to RP whether they heard that whisper or not, and whether to respond to it.<br>
<br>
Great write-up, Isharra. While not everything is 100% suitable to the EQ world, a lot of it is, and should prove very useful for many many people here.<br>
<br>
As for the discussion about expressing thoughts. I think it's a very good point to discuss. Me, I will usually not express thoughts, but try to act out the implications of those. That said, sometimes it's easier to express them in an emote, but then I'll most likely expect others to react, not to ignore. While in a story you might get away with telling the reader the inner thoughts of one character, but have the other chraceters &quot;not know&quot; those, in EQ you don't have the same level of control. What's out is out.  Therefore, I'll also try not to express the bare thought, but some external sign that gives it away: tears, frowning, laughing or chuckling, getting all serious suddenly, etc. This can lead to inquiries from other character which might then reveal the thoughts and feelings behind those.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
