<br>
I really think I need to hotkey that *laugh*<br>
<br>
Showing actions -can- convey a lot.  In real life... how many times do you see, at least in a movie, someone making an action of eating to ask if someone else is hungry, or doing some sort of bandage wrapping action to indicate binding wounds.  Yes, it is a cop out to emote or say &quot;pantomines &quot;do you need...&quot;.  Yes, it's quicker, but not as rich as actually doing the pantomine.<br>
<br>
/em winces as she goes to the wounded, limping slightly, a look of determination on her face, determined to help others before tending to her own wounds.<br>
<br>
Oh... and it can be tough to remember, but the printed version of the emote always starts with the character name (and no way to put 's on it *sigh*).  If you write your emote with that in mind, it looks even niftier.<br>
<br>
/em hugs Bippin tightly <br>
&quot;Caillou hugs Bippin tightly.&quot;<br>
instead of<br>
/em I hug Bippin tightly<br>
&quot;Caillou I hug Bippin tightly.&quot;<br>
<br>
Yeah, it can take a bit of practice to talk in 3rd person, but it looks ever so nice <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Oh... and know what the &quot;canned&quot; emotes say you do, you might not want that.... /grin is &quot;Caillou grins evilly&quot;  ummm... no... I think of a grin as more impish.. not evil.  bleah... /em grins impishly<br>
<br>
Isharra, a nice start.  I should have said it was a nice topic start in my other post.<br>
<br>
OH.... and remember, to all of you reading this, no one is THE authority.  *grins impishly*<br>
<br>
But... it is much nicer to have a story which -fits- in with the Norrathian world as laid out by Verant many and many long moons ago.  There are no Gully Dwarves, no half-Orc, no Kender, no Grey Elves, etc.  Saying you are playing by AD&amp;D rules in the Norrath world.. well.. creates a clash for many of us.  If you want to see how you can develop a -similar- idea in world using the tools of the world, that is different, it doesn't throw out one world concept (the one you're playing in) for the substitution of another.  But that's just my opinion. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=isharramoonsong>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 709<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/10/02 2:52:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3258.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Introduction to Roleplaying</span><hr size=1> You know, you're all right. Fuck me. I'm a shitty roleplayer. <br>
